<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-11-14T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-11-14T02:00:00-05:00" n="678" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d678">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">151.096/144: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-11-14T15:00:00+08:00">November 14, 1929—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received November 15—9:05 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>997. Department’s 372, November 12, 6 p.m. Pursuant to suggestion from
                                Gauss,<note n="66" xml:id="d678fn66">Clarence E. Gauss, Consul
                                General at Tientsin.</note> a note along the lines indicated was
                            sent to the Foreign Office October 22; it was tactfully worded and I do
                            not apprehend that it will furnish occasion for repercussion. Copy of
                            note was sent the American Consul under cover of my despatch Number
                            2412, November 1st.<note n="67" xml:id="d678fn67">Not
                            printed.</note></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>